On hand-drawn animation, I think you’ve identified something that goes beyond nostalgia.

When we know something was hand drawn, we’re often aware—consciously or not—that every line reflects a sequence of human choices. Each frame is evidence of attention. That changes how we perceive the work.

It’s not simply “imperfections look good.” It’s that the process itself becomes part of the experience. Viewers can mentally simulate the artist making those marks:

* “Someone chose this pose.”
* “Someone decided this expression mattered.”
* “Someone spent hours refining this motion.”

The artifact contains traces of intention.

CGI often optimizes for consistency and physical plausibility. Hand-drawn animation often optimizes for expression and emphasis. Neither is inherently superior, but they’re communicating through different constraints.

An interesting implication for AI is that perhaps it shouldn’t hide its process. Instead of a black box producing a finished video, it could expose a visible creative pipeline: rough sketch → keyframes → timing → cleanup → color → final motion. Watching the work become the work may be part of what people find meaningful.

In other words, transparency of creation can itself be an aesthetic. The audience isn’t just consuming the finished animation—they’re appreciating the chain of decisions that brought it into existence. That appreciation may be one reason hand-crafted media often feels so alive, even when the final image is less technically “perfect.”